            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kian Reza\u2019s life is a story told in carefully curated layers, much like the exhibitions he directs. Born in Sunnyvale to Iranian parents who had immigrated to the Bay Area just before the 1979 revolution, his childhood home was a testament to a culture they feared losing. While his friends\u2019 homes had video games, Kian\u2019s was filled with the aroma of saffron, the intricate patterns of Persian rugs, and the lyrical cadence of his father reading Hafez. This upbringing didn't make him feel different, but rather that he was a keeper of a story.\n\nHe pursued this instinct at San Francisco State University, choosing Museum Studies over a more lucrative tech or medical path, much to his parents' initial quiet concern. A transformative internship at the de Young Museum solidified his purpose. He wasn\u2019t just interested in artifacts; he was captivated by the narrative power they held\u2014the ability of a single object to convey a thousand unspoken words about history, struggle, and identity.\n\nHis career was a meticulous climb. He started as an assistant coordinator, learning the granular details of loan agreements and lighting design. His talent for weaving compelling narratives from disparate collections earned him a reputation for creating exhibitions that were both intellectually rigorous and emotionally resonant. Now, as Director of Exhibitions at a prominent SF historical aociety, he balances budgets and creative vision, his days a mix of spreadsheets and centuries-old artifacts.\n\nKian found his niche in a rent-controlled Hayes Valley one-bedroom, a perfect hub for his life. His 2.8-mile commute on the Muni is a cherished ritual, a time to observe the city\u2019s daily ballet before immersing himself in its history. His social life is a small, curated circle of friends\u2014an architect, a chef, a novelist\u2014with whom he shares dinners and debates. Though currently single after a long-term relationship ended amicably a few years prior, he\u2019s content, believing connection, like a good exhibition, can't be rushed.\n\nHis deepest aspiration is to one day spearhead a major exhibition on the Iranian diaspora in California, a project that would braid his professional expertise with the threads of his own family\u2019s journey. For Kian, San Francisco isn't just a place to live; it\u2019s a living museum, and he is one of its most dedicated storytellers."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe\u2019s nine, sprawled on the Persian rug in their Sunnyvale living room, the scent of cardamom tea in the air as his father\u2019s voice recites Hafez. Kian traces the intricate knots in the wool, realizing for the first time they weren\u2019t just decorations, but a map of a place he\u2019d never seen. It wasn\u2019t a feeling of loss, but of profound inheritance. In that moment, he stopped being just a boy in a room and became the keeper of a story, a path chosen before he even knew what a museum was.\n\n2.\nIt was a simple, tarnished silver locket from the 1920s, part of a small collection he was cataloging during his de Young internship. Inside, there was no photo, only a single, folded piece of sheet music. The object\u2019s quiet longing hit him with the force of a physical blow. That afternoon, the abstract idea of \"narrative power\" became visceral. He wasn't just handling history; he was holding a love story, a silent song. It cemented his belief that the smallest objects often tell the loudest truths.\n\n3.\nOpening night of his first solo-curated exhibit, \u201cPortals of the Fillmore.\u201d Kian stood by the exit, a nervous wreck. Then he watched an elderly man stop before a photograph of a torn-down Victorian, his eyes welling up. The man turned to his daughter and began telling a story from his own childhood, prompted by the display. In that instant, all the budget anxieties vanished. He knew he had succeeded: he hadn\u2019t just built an exhibition, he had built a bridge between a person and their own past.\n\n4.\nA year after his breakup, riding the N-Judah home on a foggy Tuesday. The windows were steamy, framing the city lights in a soft glow. He wasn\u2019t heading toward a shared dinner, but toward his own quiet space. A profound sense of peace washed over him. The city, with its rhythmic clatter and anonymous companionship, was its own kind of partner. He realized then that his contentment wasn't a placeholder for romance, but a deeply rooted, fulfilling relationship with San Francisco itself.\n\n5.\nLast Nowruz, at his parents\u2019 home. He finally laid out his full vision for the Iranian diaspora exhibition, describing how a simple samovar could tell the story of their flight and resettlement. He watched his father, a man of quiet concerns, look from Kian to his mother. There was a glimmer of something new in his eyes\u2014not just pride, but recognition. Kian understood then that his life\u2019s work wasn't a departure from his heritage, but its modern, living continuation, finally understood by the people who started his story."
